{"11100":{"id":11100,"short_name":"'Umar bin Qatada al-Ansari","full_name":"'Umar bin Qatada b. al-Nu'man b. Zayd b. 'Amir b. Sawad b. Zafar b. al-Khazraj b. 'Amr","arabic":"عمر بن قتادة بن النعمان","rank":2,"birth_date":"","birth_place":"Medinah","death_date":"","death_place":"Medinah","death_cause":"Natural","city":"Medinah","father_name":"233","mother_name":"","interests":"4","bio":"","children":"11103","siblings":"","spouses":"","teachers":"233,11045","students":"11103","kunya":""},"11101":{"id":11101,"short_name":"Sharhbayl bin Sa'd","full_name":"Sharhbayl bin Sa'd","arabic":"شرحبيل بن سعد أبو سعد الخطمي","rank":2,"birth_date":"","birth_place":"Medina","death_date":"123 AH/740 CE","death_place":"","death_cause":"Natural","city":"Medina","father_name":"","mother_name":"","interests":"4,8,7","bio":"","children":"","siblings":"","spouses":"","teachers":"49,479,13,38,30,1703,17,18,34","students":"11062,11107,11061,11894,11718,11234,20177,20001,كني عنه,20504,11390,كناه","kunya":"Abu Sa'd"},"11102":{"id":11102,"short_name":"Wahb bin Munabbih al-Abnavi","full_name":"Wahb bin Munabbih bin Kamil b. Sayj b. Dhi Kanaz","arabic":"وهب بن منبه الأبناوي","rank":2,"birth_date":"34 AH/654 CE","birth_place":"","death_date":"110 AH/728 CE","death_place":"","death_cause":"Natural","city":"Yemen,Dhamar","father_name":"","mother_name":"","interests":"7,8,4","bio":"He seems to have been a South Arabian of possibly Persian origin with a deep knowledge of Jewish and Christian scriptures and traditions. Wahb wrote the Kitab al-Mubtada , which inspired many Muslim versions of the lives of the prophets. However, much was attributed to him for which he was not responsible. Wahb collected the maghazi , and this has been confirmed by the discovery of a fragment of the lost work on papyri written in 228/842, the so-called Heidelberg papyrus. Wahb himself did not know of the use of isnads, that is the chain of transmitters of a particular tradition. Ibn Ishaq, Ibn Sa'd, al-Tabari, and al-Waqidi do not use Wahb for the life of the Prophet but for the beginnings of Christianity in South Arabia.\n<br>\nوهب بن منبه بن كامل بن سيح بن ذي كناز اليماني الصنعاني الذماري أبو عبد الله الأبناوي","children":"18588,19436","siblings":"11447,16633,Ma'qil,Ghilan","spouses":"","teachers":"13,38,17,18,29,34,19,19934,أبي خليفة البصري,11447,Others","students":"18588,19436,28405,28351,28026,11081,18395,11576","kunya":"Abu 'Abdullah"},"11103":{"id":11103,"short_name":"Asim bin 'Umar bin Qatada al-Ansari","full_name":"Asim bin 'Umar bin Qatada b. al-Nu'man b. Zayd b. 'Amir b. Sawad b. Zafar b. al-Khazraj b. 'Amr","arabic":"عاصم بن عمر بن قتادة","rank":2,"birth_date":"","birth_place":"Medinah","death_date":"120 AH/737 CE","death_place":"Medinah","death_cause":"Natural","city":"Medinah/Damascus","father_name":"11100","mother_name":"","interests":"7,8,4","bio":"He lectured in Damascus on the maghazi of the Prophet and his Companions, and probably committed his lectures to writing, though this is much disputed by skeptics who point out that this claim is based on later writings. He does not always cite his authorities or isnads. Ibn Ishaq seems to have attended al-Ansari's lectures..","children":"al-Fadl","siblings":"","spouses":"","teachers":"11100,34,1830,919,19,11156,11706,11045,Others","students":"Son,11154,11517,11163,11894,11209,11107,10616,11105,10628","kunya":"Abu Muhammad, Abu 'Amr"},"11104":{"id":11104,"short_name":"'Abdullah bin Abi Bakr bin Muh. b. 'Amr","full_name":"'Abdullah bin Abi Bakr bin Muhammad bin 'Amr bin Hazm","arabic":"عبد الله بن أبي بكر بن محمد بن عمرو","rank":2,"birth_date":"","birth_place":"Medina","death_date":"130 AH/747CE or 135 AH/752 CE","death_place":"","death_cause":"Natural","city":"Medina","father_name":"11239","mother_name":"","interests":"4,19,7,8","bio":"He was one of Ibn Ishaq's most important informants. There is no evidence of any book by Abdullah, and he does not seem to have bothered with isnads when passing down traditions to his hearers.","children":"","siblings":"11214,20661","spouses":"","teachers":"11239,11455,19,11157,11011,639,11874,11198,11442,10511,10633,11061,11013,Other from peers","students":"11013,11070,11107,20005,20012,20169,20506,20510,20511","kunya":"Abu Muhammad, Abu Bakr"},"11105":{"id":11105,"short_name":"Muhammad bin 'Abdur Rahman","full_name":"Muhammad bin 'Abdur Rahman bin Naufal b. al-Aswad b. Naufal b. Khuwaylid b. Asad","arabic":"محمد بن عبد الرحمن بن نوفل","rank":2,"birth_date":"","birth_place":"Medina","death_date":"131 AH/748 CE or 137 AH/754 CE","death_place":"Medina","death_cause":"Natural","city":"Medina","father_name":"'Abdur Rahman bin Naufal b. al-Aswad","mother_name":"","interests":"4,8,7","bio":"He wrote a book of maghazi that seems to remain faithful to Urwa bin al-Zubayr in its essentials.","children":"","siblings":"","spouses":"","teachers":"10511,11045,11005,11178,سالم مولى شداد,سالم بن عبد الله بن عمرو الأعرج,11023,11542,Others","students":"11013,11236,11107,20001,20377,20375,25345,11409,26010,20438,20023,20624,20020,20157","kunya":"Abu al-Aswad(أبو الأسود)"},"11106":{"id":11106,"short_name":"Musa bin 'Uqba","full_name":"Musa bin 'Uqba bin Abi 'Ayaash al-Asadi","arabic":"موسى بن عقبة","rank":2,"birth_date":"55 AH/674 CE","birth_place":"Medinah","death_date":"141AH/758 CE","death_place":"Madinah","death_cause":"Natural","city":"Medina","father_name":"'Uqba b. Abi 'Ayaash al-Asadi","mother_name":"","interests":"7,8,4,5","bio":"Client of Family of Az-Zubair Al-Awaam.<br>\nHe wrote a book on Maghaazi. A fragment of his work has survived and was published by Sachau in 1904, the so-called Berlin manuscript. Many distinguished traditionists felt his book was the most important and trustworthy of all, rivaling that of his contemporary Ibn Ishaq, and yet, surprisingly, not much of his work has survived. Ibn Ishaq himself never mentions him, though he is quoted by later historians like al-Tabari, al-Waqidi, and others. Musa for his part leaned heavily on al-Zuhri, much idealizing the Prophet.","children":"","siblings":"11125,11126","spouses":"","teachers":"740,11014,10567,11013,11014,11011,11165,11197,11059,11023,11048,11222,10511,11183,11687,11013,11187,Others","students":"20154,11154,11062,20001,20155,20173,20299,20012,20005,20160,11070,20167,20421,20187,20025,20178,28590,20157,20328","kunya":"Abu Muhammad"},"11107":{"id":11107,"short_name":"Ibn Ishaq","full_name":"Muhammad bin Ishaq bin Yasar bin Khayar","arabic":"محمد بن إسحاق بن يسار‎","rank":2,"birth_date":"85 AH/704 CE","birth_place":"Medinah","death_date":"150 AH/767 CE","death_place":"Baghdad","death_cause":"Natural","city":"Medina/Kufa/Egypt/Baghdad","father_name":"11120","mother_name":"","interests":"7,8,4","bio":"He is one of our main authorities on the life and times of the Prophet. His family was involved in transmissions of Hadith and Ibn Ishaq followed suit. He left Medina where he was born for good, probably because of the enmity of certain people like the traditionist Malik b. Anas; he eventually settled in Baghdad. Apart from the Sira he is also credited with a Kitab al Khulafa (sometimes called Ta\\\\'rikh al-khulafa\\\\'--A History of the Caliphs ) and a book of Sunan . His reputation seems to have varied considerably among the early Muslim critics; some found him very sound (e.g., al-Zuhri, who spoke of him as \\\\the most knowledgeable of men in maghazi \\\\\"), while others regarded him as a liar in relation to Hadith (e.g., al-Athram, Sulayman al-Taymi, and Wuhayb b. Khalid). However, it is of the utmost importance to realize that the Sira of Ibn Ishaq is not extant in its original form, and is not preserved as a single work. \"","children":"","siblings":"11108,11109","spouses":"","teachers":"11120,11121,11122,11197,11817,1134,11213,10535,11215,11103,11697,11013,11048,11066,11125,11279,11164,11063,11064,11168,11427,11061,11104,12201,11056,11029,11709,11209,10606,18893,19961,11222,19826,11411,11233,19192,11065,11545,10526,Several Others","students":"11062,11411,(His Shaikh),11272,11184,11071,30498,20021,20022,20020,20012,20005,20321,20102,20468,20469,20246,20337,20028,20322,20326,28221,20356,20672,30213,20183,20304,20472,20118,20734","kunya":"Abu 'Abdullah, Abu Bakr"},"11108":{"id":11108,"short_name":"Abu Bakr bin Ishaq","full_name":"Abu Bakr bin Ishaq bin Yasar bin Khayar","arabic":"أبو بكر بن إسحاق بن يسار","rank":2,"birth_date":"","birth_place":"Medina","death_date":"","death_place":"Baghdad","death_cause":"Natural","city":"Medina/Baghdad","father_name":"11120","mother_name":"","interests":"4","bio":"","children":"","siblings":"11107,11109","spouses":"","teachers":"11699,19822,12963","students":"11107,11411","kunya":""},"11109":{"id":11109,"short_name":"'Umar bin Ishaq","full_name":"'Umar bin Ishaq bin Yasar bin Khayar","arabic":"عمر بن إسحاق بن يسار","rank":2,"birth_date":"","birth_place":"Medina","death_date":"~154 AH","death_place":"Medina","death_cause":"Natural","city":"Medina","father_name":"11120","mother_name":"","interests":"4","bio":"","children":"","siblings":"11107,11108","spouses":"","teachers":"People of Medina","students":"'Abdul Aziz bin Muhammad,Abu Bakr al-Hanfi","kunya":"Abu Hafs"},"11110":{"id":11110,"short_name":"Abu Maryam al-Thaqafi","full_name":"Iyas ibn Dubayah b. Muhtarish b. 'Abd 'Amr b. 'Ubaid b. Malik b. 'Abdullah b. al-dool b. Hanifa","arabic":"أبو مريم الثقفي إياس بن ضبيح","rank":2,"birth_date":"","birth_place":"Yemen","death_date":"","death_place":"Sanbil, part of Ahwaz","death_cause":"Natural","city":"Yemen/Basrah/Kufa","father_name":"","mother_name":"","interests":"4,19","bio":"He was one of the people of Yeman and was one of the followers of Musaylima.  He killed Zayd ibn al_Khattab in the Battle of Yamama.  Then he repented and became Muslims and was a good Muslim. He was appointed qadi of Basra after 'Imran ibn al-Husayn in the time of 'Umar ibn al-Khattab.  He has few hadiths.\n","children":"'Abdullah bin Iyas","siblings":"","spouses":"","teachers":"3,4,5,37","students":"19084,22611","kunya":"Abu Maryam"},"11111":{"id":11111,"short_name":"K'ab bin Suwar al-Azdy","full_name":"K'ab bin Suwar b. Bakr b. 'Abd b. Tha'laba b. Salim b. Dhal b. Laqit b. al-Harith b. Malik...b. Daus","arabic":"كعب بن سور الأزدي","rank":2,"birth_date":"","birth_place":"Basra","death_date":"36 AH","death_place":"","death_cause":"Killed(Jamal)","city":"Basra","father_name":"Suwar b. Bakr","mother_name":"'A'isha","interests":"4,19","bio":"He was a man known for his virtue and righteousness but does not have any hadith.  He was appointed Qadi by 'Umar ibn al-Khattab after he noticed something in a case that 'Umar ibn al-Khattab did not notice.  Ash-Sha'bi said, A woman came to 'Umar ibn al-Khattab and said, 'I complain to you of the best of the people of this world unless some man had done it before him or done the like of what he does.  He stands in prayer for the entire night until morning, and fasts the day until evening.'  Then modesty and embarrassment overcame her and she said, 'Dismiss me, Amir al-Mu'minin.'  He said, 'May Allah repay you well. Excellent is the praise you have uttered. I have dismissed you.'  When she had gone away, Ka'b ibn Suwar said, Amir al-Mu'minin, she has been eloquent in her complain.'  He asked, ‘What was she complaining about?'  He replied, 'Her husband.'  He said, 'I owe the woman a response.'  He told Ka'b, 'Judge between them.'  He said, 'Me judge when you are present?'  He said, 'You grasped what I did not grasp.'  Ka'b said, 'Allah says, \"Marry other permissible women, two, three or four [4:3].\" Therefore fast three days and break the fast for a day on one day.  Stand in prayer for three nights and spend one night with her.'  'Umar said, 'This is more wondrous to me than the first!'  So he sent him as a qadi to the people of Basra.\"  \n\nThe story of how he died are told by some people of knowledge who say that when Talha, az-Zubayr and 'A'isha came to Basra, Ka'b ibn Suwar went into a house and had it covered with clay, leaving only a hole from which to receive his food and drink.  This was in order to withdraw from the fitna.  'A'isha was told, \"If Ka'b ibn Suwar comes out with you, none of Azd [his tribe] will hold back.\"  So she rode to him and called to him and spoke to him, but he did not answer her.  She said, \"Ka'b! Am I not your mother and do I not hav ea right from you?\"  So he spoke to her.  She said, \"I want to make peace between the people!\"  That was when he came out and took the Qur'an and opened it and walked between the rows calling them to what is contained.  An arrow came from an unknown source and killed him.\n\"","children":"","siblings":"","spouses":"","teachers":"3","students":"","kunya":""},"11112":{"id":11112,"short_name":"al-Ahnaf bin Qays","full_name":"al-Dahhak/Sakhr bin Qays b. Mua'wiya b. Hussain b. 'Ubada b. Nazl b. Murra b. 'Ubaid b. al-Harith","arabic":"الأحنف بن قيس بن معاوية","rank":2,"birth_date":"","birth_place":"Hijaz","death_date":"67 AH or 72 AH","death_place":"Kufa","death_cause":"Natural","city":"Hijaz, Basra, Persia, Kufa","father_name":"Qays b. Mua'wiya b. Hussain","mother_name":"Habba bint 'Amr","interests":"2,4","bio":"Full lineage : Al-Ahnaf ibn Qays b. Mua'wiyah b. Husein b. 'Ubada b. Nazl b. Murra b. 'Ubaid b. al-Harith b. 'Amr b. Ka'b b. Sa'd b. Zayd Manat b. Tamim\n<br>\nHe was a reliable and trustworthy with few hadiths.  He was born with a foot deformity (ahnaf).   He was reported to have been in a state of janaba on his way to Persia and instead of waking any of his slaves or army up, he searched for water/snow until his feet bled.  He was good friends with Mus'ab ibn az-Zubayr, the then current governor of Kufa.  He was requested by 'Abdu'l-Malik to become the ruler of Syria. \n","children":"","siblings":"","spouses":"","teachers":"3,5,4,9,16,23,Others","students":"11016,11318,10692","kunya":"Abu Bahr"},"11113":{"id":11113,"short_name":"Abu 'Uthman al-Nahdi","full_name":"Abdur-Rahman ibn Mull b. 'Amr b. Abi 'Amr b. 'Uday b. Wahab b. Rabiath b. Khuzaymah b. Ka'b b. Raf","arabic":"عبد الرحمن بن مل - أبو عثمان النهدي","rank":2,"birth_date":"","birth_place":"Kufa","death_date":"~95 AH","death_place":"Basra","death_cause":"Natural","city":"Kufa, Basra","father_name":"","mother_name":"","interests":"4,4","bio":"He was reliable.  He was alive in the time of the Messenger of Allah (ﷺ) but did not see him.  It is reported that he lived for about 130 years.  He served as a sergeant ('arif).  He died in Basra at the beginning of the governorship of Al-Hajjaj ibn Yusuf over Iraq.  He moved from Kufa to Basra for he refused to be in the city where the nephew of the Prophet was killed.","children":"","siblings":"","spouses":"","teachers":"3,5,9,6,11,16,145,23,39,50,24,4060,5040,384,28,3229,17,18,29,107,227,13,38,41,53,56,Others","students":"11269,11019,11080,11289,11317,11298,11282,11015,11279,11597,11292,10997,11600,10664","kunya":"Abu 'Uthman"},"11114":{"id":11114,"short_name":"Abu al-Aswad al-Du'ali","full_name":"Zalim bin 'Amr b. Sufyan b. Jandal b. Ya'mur b. Hunsh(Hulays) b. Tha'laba b. 'Ady b. al-Dayl","arabic":"أبو الأسود الديلي/الدؤلي","rank":2,"birth_date":"","birth_place":"Kufa","death_date":"69 AH/688 CE","death_place":"Basra","death_cause":"Natural","city":"Kufa, Basra","father_name":"'Amr b. Sufyan","mother_name":"","interests":"4,14,18,22","bio":"There are different versions of his name.<br>\nHe was apartisan poet of the Shi'a.  He was reliable in hadith.  When 'Abdullah ibn 'Abbas resigned as governor and left Basra, he delegated Abu'l Asward, ad-Du'ali in charge of it and 'Ali ibn Abi Talib conformed him.   Said to be the founder of Arabic grammar,invented a system of providing fathah, dammah and kasra to indicate some vowel sounds.\n","children":"10729","siblings":"","spouses":"","teachers":"3,5,32,23,16,7,39,41,17,123","students":"10729,11432,11316,عمر بن عبد الله مولى عفيرة,12740","kunya":"Abu al-Aswad"},"11115":{"id":11115,"short_name":"Ziyad bin Abi Sufyan","full_name":"Ziyad ibn Abi Sufyan ibn Harb","arabic":"زياد بن أبي سفيان/زياد بن أبيه","rank":2,"birth_date":"630 CE","birth_place":"Ta'if","death_date":"53 AH, 672 CE","death_place":"Kufa","death_cause":"Natural","city":"Kufa, Basra","father_name":"116","mother_name":"Sumayya","interests":"4,18","bio":"His mother was Sumayya, the slavegirl of al-Harith ibn Kalada ath-Taqafi.  He was said to have been born in the Year of the Conquest of Makkah in Ta'if.  He was governor of Basra for Mu'awiyiya after he claimed him as his brother and he later added Kufa to his jurisdiction.  He spent the winter in Basra and the summer in Kufa.  He left 'Amr ibn Hurayth in charge of Kufa when he left it, and Samura ibn Jundub over Basra when he left it.  He is neither a recitor nor a faqih but he was well-known and a scribe for Abu Musa al-Ash'ari.   He died in Kufa while he was governor there for Mu'awiya ibn Abi Sufyan\n","children":"","siblings":"27","spouses":"","teachers":"3","students":"","kunya":""},"11116":{"id":11116,"short_name":"Karima bint al-Miqdad ibn al-Aswad","full_name":"Karima bint al-Miqdad ibn 'Amr b. Tha'laba b. Malik b. Rabi'ah b. 'Amir al-Bahrani, al-Kindi","arabic":"كريمة بنت المقداد بن عمرو","rank":2,"birth_date":"","birth_place":"Medina","death_date":"","death_place":"Medina","death_cause":"Natural","city":"Medina","father_name":"163","mother_name":"248","interests":"2,4","bio":"","children":"22709,22717,19512","siblings":"911,910","spouses":"2308","teachers":"248","students":"2308,19512","kunya":""},"11118":{"id":11118,"short_name":"Abu Bakr bin Salim b. 'Abdullah b. 'Umar","full_name":"Abu Bakr bin Salim bin 'Abdullah ibn 'Umar bin al-Khattab b. Nufayl b. 'Abdul-'Uzza b. Riyah","arabic":"أبو بكر بن سالم بن عبد الله بن عمر","rank":2,"birth_date":"","birth_place":"Medina","death_date":"","death_place":"Medina","death_cause":"Natural","city":"Medina","father_name":"11011","mother_name":"Umm Hakam bint Yazid bin 'Abd Qays","interests":"4","bio":"","children":"","siblings":"'Umar,'Abd